stylization associated with that position—to understand the actor/stage location relationship in Shakespeare’s plays. In his examination of the original staging of Shakespeare’s tragedies, Mooney looks at the traditional interplay between a downstage “place” and upstage “location” to describe the difference between non-illusionistic action (often staged near the audience) and the illusionistic, localized action that characterizes mimetic art.The innovative and insightful approach of Shakespeare’s Dramatic Transactions brings together the techniques of performance criticism and the traditional literary study of Shakespearean tragedy. In showing how the distinctions of stage location illuminate the interaction among language, representation, Mooney’s compelling argument enhances our understanding of Shakespeare and the theater.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aTheater audienceszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheater audienceszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aDRAMA / Shakespeare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z97831107136020 cprintz978082231039640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382836?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382836423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822382836/original  a978-3-11-071360-2  Duke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles